#1:

Cancer remains one of the leading causes of morbidity and mortality worldwide, representing a major and growing public health challenge. The global burden of cancer continues to increase, driven by population aging, lifestyle transitions, and environmental exposures. Developing successful preventative programs, allocating resources, and identifying people at highest risk all depend on an understanding of patterns and trends in cancer incidence.

This study utilizes data from the Global Burden of Disease (GBD) project, curated by the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME) at the University of Washington. The GBD database provides comprehensive and standardized estimates of key health indicatorsâincluding incidence, prevalence, mortality, and disability-adjusted life years (DALYs)âfor more than 200 countries and territories.

In this analysis, datasets from 2022 and 2023 were examined to explore global patterns of cancer incidence. The dataset includes information on multiple cancer types (e.g., breast, lung, colorectal), stratified by sex, country, and year. Each observation represents a specific cancer typeâs estimated incidence rate (new cases per 100,000 population), along with its corresponding 95% uncertainty interval (upper and lower bounds). Together, these data allow for comparative and temporal analyses of cancer incidence worldwide.

The goal of this analysis is to explore global patterns of cancer incidence and address the following key questions:

  1. In the world, which cancer types are most common?
  2. What is the difference in cancer incidence rates between men and women?
  3. Which countries show the highest and lowest cancer incidence rates?
  4. How have global cancer incidence rates changed from 2022 to 2023?

By addressing these questions, this study aims to provide insights into the global distribution of cancer burden and highlight regional and demographic disparities that may inform future prevention and screening strategies.The results will provide insight into how cancer risks differ by region and sex, and how the global incidence landscape has evolved from 2022 through 2023.

#2:

The dataset analyzed in this project was obtained from the Global Burden of Disease (GBD) Results Tool developed by the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation (IHME), available at https://ghdx.healthdata.org/gbd-results-tool. The dataset used in this analysis was downloaded directly from the IHME data portal after registering for an account so that the most recent and standardized global cancer incidence estimates can be accessed. The GBD portal provides datasets separately for each year, the 2022 and 2023 incidence data were downloaded individually and later combined for comparative analysis.

The GBD database provides comprehensive and comparable estimates of disease burdenâincluding incidence, mortality, and disability-adjusted life years (DALYs)âacross more than 200 countries and territories.

To acquire the data, the following options were selected:

GBD Estimate: Cause

Measure: Incidence (new cancer cases)

Metric: Rate (per 100,000 population)

Years: 2022, 2023

Sex: Male, Female, Both

Cause: All neoplasms and cancer subtypes

Location: Global and all countries

The resulting CSV file was downloaded directly from the IHME portal and imported into RStudio for analysis using the readr package from the tidyverse library.

The distribution of cancer incidence rates from GBD (2022â2023) is highly right-skewed. Most cancers have low-to-moderate incidence rates (10â100 cases per 100,000), while a fewâsuch as non-melanoma skin, breast, and prostate cancersâexhibit exceptionally high rates. This pattern reflects the heterogeneity of cancer burdens across types and populations.

Overall, the dataset gbd_all includes 41,208 observations and 7 variables, combining data from 2022 and 2023. Key variables include categorical factors (cause, location, sex) and continuous measures (val, lower, upper, year). The distribution of incidence rates (val) is right-skewed, with most cancers having low rates and a few exhibiting high incidence (e.g., skin, breast, prostate). Data are evenly distributed across sexes and years, and no missing values were detected.

The highest mean incidence rates (shown in darker purple and black) were concentrated in North America, Western Europe, and Oceania, particularly in countries such as the United States, Canada, Australia, and several Northern and Central European nations. These regions report rates exceeding 200 cases per 100,000 population, reflecting both aging populations and well-developed screening and reporting systems.

In contrast, low- and middle-income regions across Africa, South Asia, and parts of the Middle East displayed substantially lower reported incidence (<100 per 100,000). This likely reflects limited cancer detection infrastructure, underdiagnosis, and incomplete cancer registry coverage rather than true epidemiological protection.

Overall, the map highlights a global northâsouth divide, underscoring the intersection of health system capacity, demographic aging, and surveillance quality as key determinants shaping observed cancer burden patterns.

The global mean cancer incidence rate increased slightly from 82.9 to 83.6 incidents per 100,000 people during 2022 and 2023. Despite the little improvement, it points to a sustained higher trend in cancer reporting and detection worldwide. Rather than a real spike in the number of new cancer cases, this increase might be the result of advancements in screening initiatives, diagnostic capabilities, and data reporting. The trend is consistent with larger global health shifts, as aging populations and improved healthcare systems lead to a steadily rising global documented incidence of cancer.

#5:

The Global Burden of Disease (GBD) 2022â2023 dataset analysis shows distinct trends in the prevalence of cancer worldwide. Non-melanoma skin, breast, colorectal, prostate, and lung cancers are the most common cancers globally, and they collectively have the greatest incidence rates. Males often have higher overall cancer incidence rates than females, primarily because of lung and prostate cancers, whereas females have higher rates of breast and cervical cancers. Geographically, lower incidence rates are seen in portions of Africa and South Asia, whereas greater rates are concentrated in high-income regions like Australia, Western Europe, and North America. This reflects both real epidemiological differences and disparities in diagnostic capacity.
